pullRequest.body:
A construction by transfinite recursion, fairly standard in set theory, but I have yet to see similar arguments in mathlib. See [module docstring](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/Field_Card_Emb/Mathlib/SetTheory/Cardinal/FieldEmb.lean#L20-L137) for more details.

I use some ad hoc category theoretical definitions: `IsNatEquiv` is [(Nat)Iso](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Iso.html#CategoryTheory.Iso) in the functor category, and `inverseLimit` is [Functor.sections](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Types.html#CategoryTheory.Functor.sections), but it may makes things unnecessarily complicated to use the category library (OrderDual would be needed for example), as the construction is fairly down to earth.

[Zulip](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/217875-Is-there-code-for-X.3F/topic/Separability.20degree.3F/near/411486335)

---

I think @digama0 @sterraf @YaelDillies @vihdzp might be interested to review this. Are you aware of other similar proofs formalized in mathlib or elsewhere? Is there anything general (about the transfinite recursion setup?) that can be extracted?

Lots of notations are introduced as shorthands in the file; if you see a way to improve them, please let me know.

Thanks! Opened #18067
According to the main result, this holds only if `Field.sepDegree F E` is infinite. So you should say "an algebraic extension with infinite separable degree".
Good catch!

Does this private local instance used in the *declarations* of the public theorems in this file? If yes, then these results can't be used by other files due to missing instance.

There are also some other private instances below.

I think as long as the types of declarations don't require the instance, they can still be used outside of this file (Edit: I see that you already recognized this point), though I don't expect them to be. My main motivation for not making them private is so that they show up in the documentation, so the reader gets a flavor of the proof without reading the code; otherwise the documentation will only contain the last 5 theorems (the main results). I've enclosed everything other than the main results in the namespace `Field.Emb.Cardinal` that probably will never be opened, so they are effectively private.

I have results similar to this:

```lean
-- TODO: should be also true with `Semiring A`
-- TODO: move to suitable place
theorem _root_.Algebra.lift_card_adjoin_le
    (R : Type u) {A : Type v} [CommSemiring R] [CommSemiring A] [Algebra R A] (s : Set A) :
    Cardinal.lift.{u} (Cardinal.mk (Algebra.adjoin R s)) â‰¤
    max (max (Cardinal.lift.{v} (Cardinal.mk R)) (Cardinal.lift.{u} (Cardinal.mk s)))
      Cardinal.aleph0 := by
  rw [Algebra.adjoin_eq_range]
  have h := Cardinal.lift_mk_le_lift_mk_of_surjective
    (MvPolynomial.aeval (R := R) (Ïƒ := s) Subtype.val).rangeRestrict_surjective
  rw [Cardinal.lift_umax, Cardinal.lift_id'.{v, u}] at h
  exact h.trans MvPolynomial.cardinal_lift_mk_le_max

-- TODO: move to suitable place
theorem _root_.IntermediateField.lift_card_adjoin_le
    (F : Type u) {E : Type v} [Field F] [Field E] [Algebra F E] (s : Set E) :
    Cardinal.lift.{u} (Cardinal.mk (adjoin F s)) â‰¤
    max (max (Cardinal.lift.{v} (Cardinal.mk F)) (Cardinal.lift.{u} (Cardinal.mk s)))
      Cardinal.aleph0 := by
  rw [(FractionRing.algEquiv (Algebra.adjoin F s) (adjoin F s)).toEquiv.symm.cardinal_eq,
    FractionRing.card (Algebra.adjoin F s)]
  exact Algebra.lift_card_adjoin_le F s
```

But maybe they should go to another PR.
Yeah, mine is about the rank while yours are about the cardinality (so they have to involve #R and #F). Would be glad to review your PR. You can write `#R` and `lift.{u}` etc. if you `open Cardinal`.
